---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base>
  <div class="page-wrapper">
    <div class="nmpp-slideshow">
      <button class="nmpp-arrow nmpp-arrow-left" aria-label="Previous slide">&#8592;</button>
      <button class="nmpp-arrow nmpp-arrow-right" aria-label="Next slide">&#8594;</button>

      <div class="nmpp-slide active">
        <img src="/images/banner1.png" alt="Magnetohydrodynamics" />
        <div class="nmpp-slide-caption">
          <div class="nmpp-slide-caption-content">
            <strong>Magnetrons</strong>
            HiPiMS devices are used for thin film deposition in the semiconductor industry.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="nmpp-slide">
        <img src="/images/banner2.png" alt="Simulation Visualization" />
        <div class="nmpp-slide-caption">
          <div class="nmpp-slide-caption-content">
            <strong>Spoke formation</strong>
            SAPIC is designed for simulating spoke formation in magnetrons. ref: J Hnilica et al 2018 J. Phys. D: Appl. Phys. 51 095204
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="nmpp-slide">
        <img src="/images/banner3.png" alt="Numerical Methods" />
        <div class="nmpp-slide-caption">
          <div class="nmpp-slide-caption-content">
            <strong>Numerical Methods</strong>
            SAPIC uses an adaptive mesh refinement (AMR) method to efficiently simulate complex geometries, and a particle-in-cell (PIC) method for plasma simulation.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nmpp-slideshow-controls">
        <span class="nmpp-dot active"></span>
        <span class="nmpp-dot"></span>
        <span class="nmpp-dot"></span>
      </div>
    </div>

    SAPIC is a 3D-PIC AMR code developed at the Laboratoire des Gaz et des Plasmas (LPGP) in Paris, France.
    It is designed for the simulation of magnetized plasmas in complex geometries, with a particular focus on magnetron applications.
    SAPIC is build as an adaptive mesh refinement (AMR) code with a particle-in-cell (PIC) method for plasma simulation, and is developed in C++ with a Python interface for pre- and post-processing.

    <h2 class="section-heading" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">The SAPIC team</h2>

    <a href="https://github.com/ThinkPlasma" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Adrien</a> and <a href="https://github.com/max-models" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Max</a> are the main developers of SAPIC. We are both postdoctoral researchers at the Laboratoire des Gaz et des Plasmas (LPGP) in Paris, France, and have a background in plasma physics and computational methods.
    
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Documentation</h2>


    The documentation for SAPIC is available <a href="https://sapic-lpgp.github.io/sapic" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">here</a>.
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Reference publication</h2>

    This is the reference publication for SAPIC. Please cite this paper when using SAPIC in your research:

    ...

  </div>
</Base>

<script>
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
    const container = document.querySelector('.nmpp-slideshow');
    if (!container) return;
    const slides = Array.from(container.querySelectorAll('.nmpp-slide'));
    const dots = Array.from(container.querySelectorAll('.nmpp-dot'));
    const leftArrow = container.querySelector('.nmpp-arrow-left');
    const rightArrow = container.querySelector('.nmpp-arrow-right');
    let current = 0;
    let interval: ReturnType<typeof setInterval> | null = null;

    function showSlide(idx: number) {
      slides.forEach((s, i) => s.classList.toggle('active', i === idx));
      dots.forEach((d, i) => d.classList.toggle('active', i === idx));
      current = idx;
    }

    function next() { showSlide((current + 1) % slides.length); }
    function prev() { showSlide((current - 1 + slides.length) % slides.length); }

    function resetInterval() {
      if (interval) clearInterval(interval);
      interval = setInterval(next, 5000);
    }

    dots.forEach((dot, i) => {
      dot.addEventListener('click', () => { showSlide(i); resetInterval(); });
    });
    leftArrow?.addEventListener('click', (e) => { e.preventDefault(); prev(); resetInterval(); });
    rightArrow?.addEventListener('click', (e) => { e.preventDefault(); next(); resetInterval(); });

    showSlide(0);
    resetInterval();
  });
</script>
